To show `g.symm (f.symm x) = x`, apply `g` to both sides:

`g (g.symm (f.symm x)) = g x`.

The left side simplifies to `f.symm x` because `g.symm` is the inverse of `g`. So we have:

`f.symm x = g x`.

Now apply `f` to both sides:

`f (f.symm x) = f (g x)`.

The left side simplifies to `x` because `f.symm` is the inverse of `f`. The right side is `f (g x)`. Since `f` and `g` are inverses, `f (g x) = x`. So indeed `x = x`.

